description:
Khadi and Village Industries Development Program aims at increasing employment and income in the Khadi and Village Industries (KVI) subsector of rural nonfarm sector.  It supports ADB's core strategy of inclusive social development, as it will benefit rural poor and small producer organizations, who/which are dependent on the KVIs for their income. The Program aims at: 
(i) establishing a policy reform and implementation framework to carry out the intended reforms; 
(ii) promoting and marketing khadi by establishing a khadi mark and a majority privately owned marketing organization (MO); 
(iii) enhancing raw material production and procurement efficiencies, introducing market-linked pricing, shift to production incentives in lieu of sales rebate, assessing working capital for khadi institutions and facilitating access to working capital, encouraging entrepreneurs, and empowering artisans; and  
(iv) implementing institutional reforms in Khadi and Village Industries Commission (KVIC), revitalizing khadi institutions, building capacity and synergizing with village industries.

Project overview>> Professional Assistance For Development Action (PRADAN) is one of ICCO’s long-term partners. With three decades of experience of poverty reduction, PRADAN sees its major future role as an enabler of large-scale poverty alleviation efforts particularly in the Central Indian Tribal Region, which is the poverty heartland of India. As PRADAN’s grassroots work expands to poorer and more remote areas, new intervention prototypes need to be developed to contribute to sustainable livelihoods, while more mature interventions will need to be hived off to stand on their own feet. PRADAN realizes that after decades of functioning as a large-scale implementing organization, a paradigm shift is required if it is to effectively scale up and deepen its impact. PRADAN therefore strives to become a facilitator of coordinated action among diverse stakeholders, exchanging knowledge and know-how with various actors, improving and increasing the pool of people and organizations engaged with the poor, and orchestrating multi-stake holder engagements to improve livelihoods and well-being of the marginalized.
Project activities and outputs>> During this project period, PRADAN will proactively identify, create linkages and engage with other stakeholders in a systematic manner to accomplish these objectives. ICCO’s support will be directed towards enabling PRADAN to build the required capabilities to manage this transition. The concrete areas of support are: 
- Providing seed capital to create internal capacities and systems to effectively manage broad-based core institutional support from longstanding partners like ICCO and Tata Trust, while attracting new financing from other societal actors, including Indian corporations, foundations and individuals; 
- Providing institutional support to create “new growth” nuclei in Rajasthan and Bihar; 
- Building partnerships with the private sector for mature business interventions;  and 
- Strengthening partnership work with other NGOs.

Project background>> The Government of Bihar, one of the poorest states in India, has prepared its Agriculture road map for 2012-17. The plan aims to increase the average crop intensity to 243% from 85% with the investment of INR 1,500 billion. Investment for good quality seeds and technical support from KVK (Farm Research Center) and Agriculture department are the key feature of the plan. The state’s Irrigation Department also plans to launch Bihar Satabadi Private Tube Scheme of implementing 7.5 lakh tube wells during this period, with an investment of INR 80 million. These investments open up opportunities for pro-poor value chain development in the state. Saral Services is an NGO that focuses on leveraging the power of technology to enhance the livelihoods of the poor in Patna and in Nalanda Districts of Bihar. As part of the process of operationalizing of its Multi-Annual Strategic Plan (MASP 2020), ICCO seeks to broker strong relationships between civil society, corporate sector and government initiatives for base-of-the-pyramid interventions.
Project overview>> The main objective of this project is to establish livelihood eco-systems for the poorest in Bihar, especially in the vegetable/non cereal sub sector. The project will work with a diverse network of agencies (governmental, NGO and businesses) to establish vibrant clusters of production, processing and retailing, with a robust IT infrastructure to support the development of the selected value chains. 
Project activities and outputs>> 
- Undertaking a baseline study of the vegetable/non cereal landscape in Bihar to understand the present status of the crop and associated farmers, including the poorest. The study will build on the experiences of key actors in the state including PRADAN, BRLP, ASA and the Department of Agriculture;
- Convening a consultative workshop in Patna on “Livelihood Eco-Systems for the poorest and GoB Roadmap of Agriculture 2012-17” that will bring together NGOs working to improve the livelihoods of the poorest communities in Bihar, as well as government institutions and other development partners, including SDTT, SRTT, AKF and ICCO;  
- Developing a pilot project on the vegetable value chain involving 500 households;
- Establishing a value chain network with other interested NGOs to support inclusive market development in Bihar, under the coordination of Saral Services.

Project overview>> RDA and TSRD are well-established community development organizations focusing on social and right-based work in support of the poorest communities, and with dedicated field staff. The two organizations are also members of the VBN, which is a network of 18 NGOs working in state of Jharkhand. Since joining VBN, RDA and TSRD have incorporated market-based livelihood promotion in their programs, reaching 2,000 smallholder producers within the first year alone. The coalition aims to further scale this initiative in the Patanda, Ghatshila and Bhulbamgarh blocks of Jharkhand, with support from VBN and PRADAN. This area is very suitable for growing vegetables, especially tomato. However, the poorest farmers lack sufficient capital to invest in their farms and cannot access larger markets where they can earn better prices. The two organizations therefore aim to help the farmers to establish strong producer organizations at village level, with an federation of producer organizations at state level to enable smallholder farmers to access the market and increase their income from tomato and vegetable farming.
Project activities and outputs>> 
- Establishing 50 village-level farmers organizations and two cooperatives, representing 2000 smallholder farmers;
- Providing training to farmers on improved agricultural production and processing techniques to diversify income sources; 
- Enhancing partnerships with government institutions, financial services, research organizations, seed and fertilizer companies and local traders;
- Exploring the feasibility of forming an apex state level federation of smallholder producers to provide all required services and marketing linkages in future. 
Expected outcomes>>
- 4000 smallholder producers organized in producer organizations;
- Smallholders increase their income, earning an average of Rs.10,000 for 0.25 acre of land.

Project overview>> This research fund aims to identify entry points for value chain interventions and social entrepreneurship activities in India. The fund will also target emerging organizations that want to test new and innovative approaches to value chain document. The main components of the project are:
- Undertaking a scoping study on potential of producing coriander spice for the international market, in partnership with the Dutch company Nedspice;
- Working with farmers organizations involved in coriander production to understand the problems faced in scaling up production to meet market demand;
- Conducting workshops to promote social entrepreneurship, followed by a call for applications for business proposals that could be incubated by ICCO India Trust.

Project background>> India is the largest turmeric producer, consumer and exporter in the world. The states of Andhra Pardesh, Tamil Nadu and Odisha respectively contribute 61%, 16% and 7% of the country's production. However, productivity of turmeric in Odisha, at around 2.5 Ton/ha is upto three times lower than the other states as farmers still use traditional methods and organic practices. While this can be seen as an advantage, the findings of a value chain analysis conducted by South Odisha Development Initaitive (SODI) revealed that the turmeric subsector faces many constraints, including the scarcity of traditional mulching material, an exploitative trading system and decline  of prices, all of which reduce the viability of turmeric cultivation as a livelihood option for the many farmers. 
Project overview>> This pilot project aims to enhance the productivity of 2,100 resource poor farmers in three disadvantaged districts the state by developing a model of joint cooperation for pro-poor value chain development. The project is implemented by a consortium of partners active in Odissa - Pradan, Harsha Trust, RCDC, Pragati and OPDSC Chetna Organic - and managed by the Madhyam Foundation, who is also the project holder for SODI. The pilot aims focus on working with a small group of poor producers to increase their productivity, while making small, but important linkages at the higher end of the value chain to facilitate market access for the farmers. ICCO will not only support the project financially, but will try to secure more funds for scaling up the project after the conclusion of the pilot phase. ICCO will also explore strategic collaborations with other actors such as IDH and the Rainforest Alliance. Specific interventions to be carried out by the project include:
- Improving seed selection and production techniques for higher yield;
- Introduction of processing techniques such as boiling and drying to reduce post harvest losses;
- Strengthening institutional mechanisms for better bargaining with market;
- Providing access to credit for farmers

Project overview>> Kutch Nav Nirman Abhiyan (Abhiyan), is a collective of Kutch-based development organizations with a strong local presence. The objective of the network is to synergize human knowledge, physical and financial resources to for community-led governance in Kutch (Gujarat state), which is the second largest district of India covering 4000 square kilometers in one of the most ecologically fragile zones of the country. Kutch is predominantly arid and susceptible to extreme climatic conditions and the frequent failure of the agriculture and animal husbandry. 
Project activities and outputs>> The project aims to enhance the income and food and nutrition security of 3,500 poor farmers, including 1650 women farmers and 580 landless laborers in 145 villages. The project also aims to strengthen six producer companies (of which two are women’s organizations) for the sustainable development of agriculture and livestock production systems the district. The project contributes to the vision of ICCO’s MASP 2020 strategic framework as it aims to contribute to sustained improvements in the availability, affordability and accessibility of food at household level in the most marginal states of the country. Specific planned activities include:
- Expanding cattle rearing and improved crop and livestock management leading to increased milk production for improved food and nutrition security and generating a cash income for households;
- Enhancing women’s role in animal husbandry;
- Undertaking surveys and needs assessments at community level;
- Strengthening and capacity building of village level groups under the supervision of producer companies; 
- Capacity building of local leaders and community workers, especially women;
- Establishment of linkages between producer companies and governmental structures.

Project overview>> Anantapur District in the state of Andhra Pradesh is one of the poorest regions in the country, characterized by small-scale and marginal agriculture, with most farmers owning less than 5 acres of land. The district experiences chronic drought owing to which there is extensive crop loss every seven out of ten years. Malnutrition, illiteracy, illnesses, deprivation, and caste and gender discrimination in Anantapur are higher than the state average. This project builds on the project “Promotion of Sustainable Agriculture & Diversified Livelihoods” pioneered by AF, but focuses on scaling up actions at farmer level by enhancing the capacity of government institutions to implement watershed development programs. The project aims to reach about 62, 000 families in 230 villages in 8 mandals of Anatapur district to enhance food and nutritional security, income security, enhanced livelihoods, gender and social equity, eco-friendly farming practices and public awareness and advocacy for appropriate and sustainable agricultural policies. The project aims to contribute to the following specific objectives: i) Strengthening 856 producer groups and their federations to work in a coordinated way in order to achieve their development goal; reduce the cost of cultivation and mitigate drought through diversified cropping and other sustainable agricultural practices on 11,200 ha of land belonging to 5,600 farmer families (35% of the 16,000 target farmer families); (ii) Supporting 15,000 farmers to adopt low carbon farming on 12,000 ha of land in order to qualify for carbon revenues; (iii) Diversifying the livelihoods of 3,237 youth from the target families through alternate off-farm/non-farm activities; (iv) Raising public awareness and lobbying the government to create favorable policies to enable the scaling up of low external input sustainable agriculture (LEISA). Overall, the project aims to make a strong contribution to ICCO’s strategic objectives relating to food & nutritional security, health, education, livelihood security and sustainability, while also advancing justice, and dignity for all by empowering the most marginalized through integrated social and economic programs.
Project activities and outputs>> 
- Creating awareness on LEISA, gender and climate change through training (10,656 participants), meetings (38,952 participants) and four exposure visits for producer organizations and federations; -
- Promoting Non-Pesticide Management (NPM) to enable 7,704 farmers to adopt NPM practices such as pest traps, application of bio-pesticides, inter and trap Crops and bird perches on 7,704  ha of farmland;
- Promoting of bio-fertilizers such as jeevamritam, farm yard manure and neem cake among 3,852 farmers;
- Providing 642 farmers provided with local cows;
- Establishing wild fruit and fodder tree crops on 161 ha of rain-fed farmland;
- Raising kitchen gardens and fruit trees around houses of 16,050 farmer women during the first year to promote home based activities;
- Providing livelihood training to rural youth (3,195 rural youth (2,500 Girls+ 695 Boys) on garment making, LMV/HMV driving, etc, to boost their off-farm options.

Project overview>> Voluntary Action Network India (VANI) is the largest apex body of voluntary organizations in the country, with a direct membership of 465 organizations and 19 network federations and an indirect membership of over 5000 organizations. VANI is also involved in strengthening similar national networks in other countries of South and South East Asia, and the Far East. VANI represents the sector’s concerns through advocacy and networking activities and raising public awareness through the media. It has lobbied the government to create a more conducive environment for the voluntary sector through reform and amendments of, among others, the Society Registration Act, Foreign Contribution Regulation Act and Income Tax Act. Under this new program focusing on governance issues for the voluntary sector, VANI will undertake research and documentation activities as well as various consultations in line with ICCO’s MASP 2020 strategic framework, which emphasizes the need to strengthen civil society movements to advance justice and dignity for all. Using a multi-stakeholder approach, the project will work with community based organizations working the most marginalized sections of society, particularly the Dalit and other minority groups, with a focus on strengthening women’s leadership in such organizations.. Hence efforts would be made of strengthening such kind of organizations. The project will target 384 VANI members, including all women-headed organizations (around 15% of VANI’s membership) and almost 2000 non-member organizations in 10 target states. It will also involve a range of government institutions whose policies have a direct impact on the livelihoods and rights of marginalized groups, including Planning Commissions, ministries of rural development, human resources, housing and urban development, health, home affairs and finance. 
Project activities and outputs>> The project will undertake both primary and secondary level data collection and convene various workshops and consultations to discuss the draft findings. In addition, VANI will convene two meetings at the regional and national level focusing on minorities issues, enabling environment, good governance policies and overall strengthening of the sector. 
Expected outcomes>> 
- 50 % of the target NGOs enhance their capacity to mobilize domestic resources, including private giving;
- 25% of the targets NGOs at grassroots level have a clear understanding of new regulatory reforms like FCRA and DTC;
- 25% of the target NGOs are following good governance practices, including basic organizational policies such as human resources and financial management and gender equity;
- There is an increase in joint programs between the government, private sector and NGOs;
- 10 % of the targets NGOs are reporting regularly to the government.

Project overview>> South Odisha Development Initiative (SODI) is an informal network of seven NGOs( Madhyam Foundation, PRADAN, RCDC, OPDSC, Pragati, Harsha Trust and Chetna Organic Farmers Association). SODI came into being in 2010 and is guided by two strategic needs: contributing to the well-being of the poor by sharing resources and expertise to enrich and expand replicable models of development in South Odisha region; and drawing strong and powerful messages from micro-level actions to influence macro-level policy reforms. Initial support from ICCO and Kerk in Actie has been instrumental in enabling SODI to demonstrate a collaborative model of working on common issues. Against this backdrop, SODI members would like to promote food and nutritional security among small and marginal farmer households, who suffer from chronic food insecurity leading to starvation, malnutrition, child and maternal deaths and migration. Moreover poor households are not able to access various entitlements put in place to alleviate this situation due to a lack of awareness and collective bargaining power. 
Project activities and outputs>> This project aims to develop a pilot mechanism to enhance access to adequate and nutritious food throughout the year for 4,000 smallholder households in 100 villages of Koraput, Malkangiri and Rayagada districts. The project will supplement an existing initiative to improve the production of pigeon pea farmers in the same area. Specific attention will given to women, infants and school going children, the elderly, and landless families. The project has two specific objectives. At the community level, it aims to enhance the productivity of assets and labor by upgrading crop production and livestock rearing practices and linking farmers to markets. At the network level, the project aims to bridge the micro-macro gap by linking community structures with government agencies and other stakeholders. The project will promote a number of activities to realize the two objectives:
(i) Expanding the cultivation and productivity of vegetables, horticultural crops, field crops and improved access to animal and human health care; 
(iI) Supporting household and community-level training and exposure to facilitate adoption of improved practices;
(iii) Facilitating the sharing of resources and expertise among partner NGOs to enrich and expand the pilot model for achieving food and nutritional security.

Project overview: Society for Aid in Development (SAD) is currently receiving support from APRODEV partner Christian Aid for a project aimed at enhancing Dalit empowerment towards increased accessibility and entitlements. In addition to strengthening state processes governing membership and support for NGOs working on land rights for landless laborers and marginal landholders, the project aims to facilitate and promote Dalit women’s leadership in land rights movements and campaigns at state and national level. The project will also initiate partnerships with stakeholders at the meso and macro levels in 15 states aimed at fostering dialogue, engagement and advocacy on Dalit land rights. The project is closely aligned to ICCO’s MASP 2020 framework, which prioritizes the empowerment of community-based organizations to enhance the rights to land and livelihoods. 
Project activities and outputs: 
- Conducting state-level workshops on women’s land rights;
- Providing paralegal trainings at zonal level;
- Carrying out fact-finding activities to document land atrocities;
- Providing legal support for land right cases;
- Carrying out state-level support activities to produce resource materials and carry out advocacy Initiatives on land rights.

Project background: Founded in 2003, the Dalit Foundation brings together nine NGO partners who are committed to the eradication of caste discrimination and the empowerment of Dalits and other marginalized communities. During the last few years the coalition has made concerted efforts to undertake joint activities towards their common objectives, primarily focused on issues related to land rights and access to education and eradication of the exploitative Devadasi networks (promoting the practice of temple prostitution). Due to the mixed success in fostering such collaborative approaches, the network also invested in systematic reflection and analysis to map its successes and failures.
Project overview: This follow up project aims to strengthen disadvantaged and excluded communities at the micro & macro levels so they can access and manage resources and exercise rights in an inclusive and participatory manner. The specific objectives include: (i) enhancing partner capacity through bonding, mutual learning and the establishment of local-global linkages; (ii) promoting women’s leadership at all levels; (iii) eradicating the practice of untouchability; and (iv) launching lobby and advocacy campaigns for pro-poor policies that enable marginalized groups to access their entitlements. 
Expected outputs: 
- Coalition member organizations and coalition functioning more effectively with better time planning and support for each other;
- All member organizations as well as the EnE coalition starts adapting a gender policy;
- Women friendly atmosphere and cultures established within each member organization;
- Invisible untouchable practices identified and strategies adapted and eradicated within each member organization;
- Welfare schemes and legal rights of the Devadasi communities accessed effectively, including their children continuing their schooling without interruption;
- Conditions for eradication of Devadasi practices established g. Improved access of pro-poor programs, schemes and policies by disadvantaged and excluded communities.

This funding will help publish and disseminate the IDRC-supported study, "Mapping Civil Society Initiatives: Toward the Development and Empowerment of Muslims in India." 

This study, which took more than two years to complete, examines eight Indian States and the region of Mewat. It documents and describes the development work being done with the Muslim community by a variety of NGOs. The NGOs represent a range of sizes, views, and approaches, including: 
- big and small;
- welfare and rights-based; 
- progressive and conservative;
- women-headed and male-headed;
- Muslim-headed, Muslim women-headed, and non-Muslim headed;
- well-funded and poorly funded;
- small towns and big cities;
- rural and urban areas; and,
- slums and villages. 

The work is qualitative and draws entirely on direct fieldwork. It successfully maps the civil society initiatives that support developing and empowering Muslims in India. 

At this time in India's history, when the government has announced its commitment to work toward developing and empowering the Muslim community, it is not clear if civil society groups are in a position to begin the long-overdue discussions around core developmental issues. The publication and wider distribution of this study will help bridge the knowledge gap about development work with Muslims. The ultimate goal is to achieve national growth with equity by providing a crucial push toward minority development in India. This research will help support policymakers in planning national development priorities for minority empowerment.
